BART Fare Formula

Timothy Sweetser

January 7, 2015

This script reads in a data file containing driving distances and fares between every pair of stations served by Bay Area Rapid Transit, as of January 1, 2013. * Self and Airport are indicator variables * Self = 1 if and only if From Station = To Station * Airport = 1 if and only if San Francisco International Airport is the To or From Station * I assume Fare is symmetric, so that traveling from Station A to Station B costs the same as B to A * SanMateo == 1 iff the trip is To or From Daly City, Colma, South San Francisco, San Bruno or Millbrae * SFO airport might be in San Mateo county, but I already have a surcharge built in for SFO trips * http://sites.google.com/site/tsweetser

setwd('/Users/timothysweetser/Box Sync/BART Project')
BART.raw <- read.csv("data/bart/BART all possible trips.csv")
source("distance correct.R")
BART.raw <- dist_correct(BART.raw)

# include each trip (one pair of stations) only once
keepers <- NULL
for (i in 1: nrow(BART.raw)) {
  sister.row <- intersect(which(BART.raw$To == BART.raw$From[i]),
                      which(BART.raw$From == BART.raw$To[i]))
  keepers <- c(keepers,min(i,sister.row,na.rm=T))
}
rm(i)
BART.fares <- BART.raw[unique(keepers), ]

# fit a linear regression model
mat <- lm(Fare ~ 0 + Miles2 + Airport*TransBay + SanMateo*TransBay, 
          # Airport:SanMateo is all 1's
          data=BART.fares,
          offset=rep(1.75,nrow(BART.fares)))

None of these interaction terms are significant at 5%: Miles2:TransBay, Miles2:Airport, Miles2:SanMateo. This means the per-mile rate is the same throughout the system.
The Millbrae-SFO trip has an extremely large, negative residual. How much do the coefficients change by excluding it?

summary(lm(Fare ~ 0 + Miles2 + Airport*TransBay + SanMateo*TransBay, 
           data=BART.fares, offset=rep(1.75,nrow(BART.fares)),
           subset=BART.fares$Station.Pair.ID != 1110))

Outliers include 911 (San Bruno - SFO), and 921 (SFO - South SF), and SFO - Millbrae.
Can the model figure out the intercept on its own?

m.int <- lm(Fare ~ Miles + Airport + TransBay, data=BART.fares)

The fitted intercept of $1.64 is pretty close.

# non airport, non transbay

# Millbrae has an average residual of +52 cents!

fareBART <- function(miles, SFO=FALSE) {
  # coefficients are from lm object 'ma'
  return (1.75 + 0.1045*miles + SFO*4.50)
}
